To further illustrate the structural inequalities of Macedonia, on the day of the 1991 referendum in which Macedonia would still declare its secession from the Socialistic Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, women aged 15 and older had the right to vote.50 Then, voters under 15 and over 71 years were also added to the top of the list of voters who could not take part in the vote, removing a mere three percent of Macedonian men from the honor of voting for Macedonia’s independence.51 The non-voters formed entirely of females were privileged by the all-male government to not be counted among the illiterate because the General Election Law of 1966 defined the illiterate as only “persons unable to read or write in any language
